{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8fe2ece6-f271-4384-a9b8-0508c07e275d","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle event mapping** in `MauiProgram.cs` via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separate.\n- Each handler receives the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS).\n- Other events are available too (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillEnterForeground`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aa6f1808-64ce-46ae-8eb5-8e351efa5d7a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI, not a codebase-specific task.","outputTokens":336,"requestId":"B7D8:396FF8:130928:190DA6:69FFD7FE"},"id":"3cbae02b-2a50-478f-8ef5-fa5960dc2adf","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:57:40.626Z","parentId":"918f4b34-8618-4aec-8324-27bb57fb8d8c"}
